Itis worth notice that a plebeian could be a senator: the social distinction between‘ patres' and‘ plebs) chiefly maintained by the denia] of the‘ ius connubii’ before the tribunate of Canuleius (4. 2, &c.)‚ had been used to exclude them from the chief official posts. But after a share in the consulship was secured to the plebs by the Lieiniau laws, 367 B.C., a new conception of nobility arose founded on tenure of office, without regard to patrician birth. Hence in later history, though the patricians retain certain honorary privileges, many plebeian families rank quite as high, and long descent was as highly valued among the one as the other.
